# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: neutralinojs
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] Within computing, **cross-platform software** (also called **multi-platform software**, **platform-agnostic software**, or **platform-independent software**) is computer software that is designed to work in several computing platforms.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] For example, a cross-platform application may run on Linux, macOS and Microsoft Windows.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform software may run on many platforms, or as few as two.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] Some frameworks for cross-platform development are Codename One, ArkUI-X, Kivy, Qt, GTK, Flutter, NativeScript, Xamarin, Apache Cordova, Ionic, and React Native.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] A hardware platform can refer to an instruction set architecture.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] For example: ARM or the x86 architecture.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] These machines can run different operating systems.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] Smartphones and tablets generally run ARM architecture, these often run Android or iOS and other mobile operating systems.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] A software platform can be either an operating system (OS) or programming environment, though more commonly it is a combination of both.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] An exception is Java, which uses an OS-independent virtual machine (VM) to execute Java bytecode.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] The Java language is typically compiled to run on a VM that is part of the Java platform.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] The Java virtual machine (Java VM, JVM) is a CPU implemented in software, which runs all Java code.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] This enables the same code to run on all systems that implement a JVM.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] Java software can be executed by a hardware-based Java processor.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] This is used mostly in embedded systems.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] Java code running in the JVM has access to OS-related services, like disk input/output (I/O) and network access, if the appropriate privileges are granted.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] The JVM makes the system calls on behalf of the Java application.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] This lets users to decide the appropriate protection level, depending on an access-control list (ACL).
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] For example, disk and network access is usually enabled for desktop applications, but not for browser-based applets.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] The Java Native Interface (JNI) can also be used to access OS-specific functions, with a loss of portability.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] Currently, Java Standard Edition software can run on Microsoft Windows, macOS, several Unix-like OSs, and several real-time operating systems for embedded devices.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] For mobile applications, browser plugins are used for Windows and Mac based devices, and Android has built-in support for Java.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] There are also subsets of Java, such as Java Card or Java Platform, Micro Edition, designed for resource-constrained devices.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] For software to be considered cross-platform, it must function on more than one computer architecture or OS.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] Developing such software can be a time-consuming task because different OSs have different application programming interfaces (API).
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] Software written for one OS may not automatically work on all architectures that OS supports.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] Just because software is written in a popular programming language such as C or C++, it does not mean it will run on all OSs that support that language—or even on different versions of the same OS.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] Web applications are typically described as cross-platform because, ideally, they are accessible from any web browser: the browser is the platform.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] Web applications generally employ a client–server model, but vary widely in complexity and functionality.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] It can be hard to reconcile the desire for features with the need for compatibility.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] Basic web applications perform all or most processing from a stateless server, and pass the result to the client web browser.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] All user interaction with the application consists of simple exchanges of data requests and server responses.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] This type of application was the norm in the early phases of World Wide Web application development.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] Such applications follow a simple transaction model, identical to that of serving static web pages.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] Today, they are still relatively common, especially where cross-platform compatibility and simplicity are deemed more critical than advanced functionality.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] Prominent examples of advanced web applications include the Web interface to Gmail and Google Maps.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] Such applications routinely depend on additional features found only in the more recent versions of popular web browsers.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] These features include Ajax, JavaScript, Dynamic HTML, SVG, and other components of rich web applications.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] Because of the competing interests of compatibility and functionality, numerous design strategies have emerged.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] Many software systems use a layered architecture where platform-dependent code is restricted to the upper- and lowermost layers.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] Graceful degradation attempts to provide the same or similar functionality to all users and platforms, while diminishing that functionality to a least common denominator for more limited client browsers.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] For example, a user attempting to use a limited-feature browser to access Gmail may notice that Gmail switches to basic mode, with reduced functionality but still of use.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] Some software is maintained in distinct codebases for different (hardware and OS) platforms, with equivalent functionality.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] This requires more effort to maintain the code, but can be worthwhile where the amount of platform-specific code is high.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] This strategy relies on having one codebase that may be compiled to multiple platform-specific formats.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] One technique is conditional compilation.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] With this technique, code that is common to all platforms is not repeated.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] Blocks of code that are only relevant to certain platforms are made conditional, so that they are only interpreted or compiled when needed.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] Another technique is separation of functionality, which disables functionality not supported by browsers or OSs, while still delivering a complete application to the user.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] (See also: Separation of concerns.) This technique is used in web development where interpreted code (as in scripting languages) can query the platform it is running on to execute different blocks conditionally.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] Third-party libraries attempt to simplify cross-platform capability by hiding the complexities of client differentiation behind a single, unified API, at the expense of vendor lock-in.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] Responsive web design (RWD) is a Web design approach aimed at crafting the visual layout of sites to provide an optimal viewing experience—easy reading and navigation with a minimum of resizing, panning, and scrolling—across a wide range of devices, from mobile phones to desktop computer monitors.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] Little or no platform-specific code is used with this technique.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform applications need much more integration testing.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] Some web browsers prohibit installation of different versions on the same machine.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] There are several approaches used to target multiple platforms, but all of them result in software that requires substantial manual effort for testing and maintenance.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] Techniques such as full virtualization are sometimes used as a workaround for this problem.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] Tools such as the Page Object Model allow cross-platform tests to be scripted so that one test case covers multiple versions of an app.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] If different versions have similar user interfaces, all can be tested with one test case.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] Web applications are becoming increasingly popular but many computer users still use traditional application software which does not rely on a client/web-server architecture.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] The distinction between traditional and web applications is not always clear.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] Features, installation methods and architectures for web and traditional applications overlap and blur the distinction.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] Nevertheless, this simplifying distinction is a common and useful generalization.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] Traditional application software has been distributed as binary files, especially executable files.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] Executables only support the platform they were built for—which means that a single cross-platform executable could be very bloated with code that never executes on a particular platform.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] Instead, generally there is a selection of executables, each built for one platform.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] For software that is distributed as a binary executable, such as that written in C or C++, there must be a software build for each platform, using a toolset that translates—transcompiles—a single codebase into multiple binary executables.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] For example, Firefox, an open-source web browser, is available on Windows, macOS (both PowerPC and x86 through what Apple Inc. calls a Universal binary), Linux, and BSD on multiple computer architectures.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] The four platforms (in this case, Windows, macOS, Linux, and BSD) are separate executable distributions, although they come largely from the same source code.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] In rare cases, executable code built for several platforms is combined into a single executable file called a fat binary.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] The use of different toolsets may not be enough to build a working executables for different platforms.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] In this case, programmers must *port* the source code to the new platform.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] For example, an application such as Firefox, which already runs on Windows on the x86 family, can be modified and re-built to run on Linux on the x86 (and potentially other architectures) as well.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] The multiple versions of the code may be stored as separate codebases, or merged into one codebase.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] An alternative to porting is *cross-platform virtualization*, where applications compiled for one platform can run on another without modification of the source code or binaries.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] As an example, Apple's Rosetta, which is built into Intel-based Macintosh computers, runs applications compiled for the previous generation of Macs that used PowerPC CPUs.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] Another example is IBM PowerVM Lx86, which allows Linux/x86 applications to run unmodified on the Linux/Power OS.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] A script can be considered to be cross-platform if its interpreter is available on multiple platforms and the script only uses the facilities built into the language.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] For example, a script written in Python for a Unix-like system will likely run with little or no modification on Windows, because Python also runs on Windows; indeed there are many implementations (e.g.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] The same goes for many of the open-source scripting languages.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] Unlike binary executable files, the same script can be used on all computers that have software to interpret the script.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] This is because the script is generally stored in plain text in a text file.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] There may be some trivial issues, such as the representation of a new line character.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform or multi-platform is a term that can also apply to video games released on a range of video game consoles.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] Examples of cross-platform games include: *Miner 2049er*, *Tomb Raider: Legend*, *FIFA series*, *NHL series* and *Minecraft*.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] Each has been released across a variety of gaming platforms, such as the Wii, PlayStation 3, Xbox 360, personal computers, and mobile devices.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] Some platforms are harder to write for than others, requiring more time to develop the video game to the same standard.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] To offset this, a video game may be released on a few platforms first, then later on others.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] Typically, this happens when a new gaming system is released, because video game developers need to acquaint themselves with its hardware and software.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] Some games may not be cross-platform because of licensing agreements between developers and video game console manufacturers that limit development to one particular console.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] As an example, Disney could create a game with the intention of release on the latest Nintendo and Sony game consoles.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] Should Disney license the game with Sony first, it may be required to release the game solely on Sony's console for a short time or indefinitely.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] Several developers have implemented ways to play games online while using different platforms.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] Psyonix, Epic Games, Microsoft, and Valve all possess technology that allows Xbox 360 and PlayStation 3 gamers to play with PC gamers, leaving the decision of which platform to use to consumers.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] The first game to allow this level of interactivity between PC and console games (Dreamcast with specially produced keyboard and mouse) was *Quake 3*.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] Games that feature cross-platform online play include *Rocket League*, *Final Fantasy XIV*, *Street Fighter V*, *Killer Instinct*, *Paragon* and *Fable Fortune,* and *Minecraft* with its Better Together update on Windows 10, VR editions, Pocket Edition and Xbox One.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform programming is the practice of deliberately writing software to work on more than one platform.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] There are different ways to write a cross-platform application.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] One approach is to create multiple versions of the same software in different *source trees*—in other words, the Microsoft Windows version of an application might have one set of source code files and the Macintosh version another, while a FOSS *nix system might have a third.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] While this is straightforward, compared to developing for only one platform it can cost much more to pay a larger team or release products more slowly.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] It can also result in more bugs to be tracked and fixed.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] Another approach is to use software that hides the differences between the platforms.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] This abstraction layer insulates the application from the platform.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] Such applications are *platform agnostic*.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] Applications that run on the JVM are built this way.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] Some applications mix various methods of cross-platform programming to create the final application.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] An example is the Firefox web browser, which uses abstraction to build some of the lower-level components, with separate source subtrees for implementing platform-specific features (like the GUI), and the implementation of more than one scripting language to ease software portability.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] Firefox implements XUL, CSS and JavaScript for extending the browser, in addition to classic Netscape-style browser plugins.
[src:neutralinojs/cross-platform-software] Much of the browser itself is written in XUL, CSS, and JavaScript.
[src:neutralinojs/document-object-model] The **Document Object Model** (**DOM**) is a cross-platform and language-independent API that treats an HTML or XML document as a tree structure wherein each node is an object representing a part of the document.
[src:neutralinojs/document-object-model] The DOM represents a document with a logical tree.
[src:neutralinojs/document-object-model] Each branch of the tree ends in a node, and each node contains objects.
[src:neutralinojs/document-object-model] DOM methods allow programmatic access to the tree; with them one can change the structure, style or content of a document.
[src:neutralinojs/document-object-model] Nodes can have event handlers (also known as event listeners) attached to them.
[src:neutralinojs/document-object-model] Once an event is triggered, the event handlers get executed.
[src:neutralinojs/document-object-model] The principal standardization of the DOM was handled by the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C), which last developed a recommendation in 2004.
[src:neutralinojs/document-object-model] WHATWG took over the development of the standard, publishing it as a living document.
[src:neutralinojs/document-object-model] The W3C now publishes stable snapshots of the WHATWG standard.
[src:neutralinojs/document-object-model] JavaScript was released by Netscape Communications in 1995 within Netscape Navigator 2.0.
[src:neutralinojs/document-object-model] Netscape's competitor, Microsoft, released Internet Explorer 3.0 the following year with a reimplementation of JavaScript called JScript.
[src:neutralinojs/document-object-model] JavaScript and JScript let web developers create web pages with client-side interactivity.
[src:neutralinojs/document-object-model] Legacy DOM was limited in the kinds of elements that could be accessed.
[src:neutralinojs/document-object-model] Form, link and image elements could be referenced with a hierarchical name that began with the root document object.
[src:neutralinojs/document-object-model] A hierarchical name could make use of either the names or the sequential index of the traversed elements.
[src:neutralinojs/document-object-model] For example, a form input element could be accessed as either `document.myForm.myInput` or `document.forms[0].elements[0]`.
[src:neutralinojs/document-object-model] The Legacy DOM enabled client-side form validation and simple interface interactivity like creating tooltips.
[src:neutralinojs/document-object-model] In 1997, Netscape and Microsoft released version 4.0 of Netscape Navigator and Internet Explorer respectively, adding support for Dynamic HTML (DHTML) functionality enabling changes to a loaded HTML document.
[src:neutralinojs/document-object-model] DHTML required extensions to the rudimentary document object that was available in the Legacy DOM implementations.
[src:neutralinojs/document-object-model] Although the Legacy DOM implementations were largely compatible since JScript was based on JavaScript, the DHTML DOM extensions were developed in parallel by each browser maker and remained incompatible.
[src:neutralinojs/document-object-model] These versions of the DOM became known as the "Intermediate DOM".
[src:neutralinojs/document-object-model] After the standardization of ECMAScript, the W3C DOM Working Group began drafting a standard DOM specification.
[src:neutralinojs/document-object-model] The completed specification, known as "DOM Level 1", became a W3C Recommendation in late 1998.
[src:neutralinojs/document-object-model] By 2005, large parts of W3C DOM were well-supported by common ECMAScript-enabled browsers, including Internet Explorer 6 (from 2001), Opera, Safari and Gecko-based browsers (like Mozilla, Firefox, SeaMonkey and Camino).
[src:neutralinojs/document-object-model] The W3C DOM Working Group published its final recommendation and subsequently disbanded in 2004.
[src:neutralinojs/document-object-model] Development efforts migrated to the WHATWG, which continues to maintain a living standard.
[src:neutralinojs/document-object-model] In 2009, the Web Applications group reorganized DOM activities at the W3C.
[src:neutralinojs/document-object-model] In 2013, due to a lack of progress and the impending release of HTML5, the DOM Level 4 specification was reassigned to the HTML Working Group to expedite its completion.
[src:neutralinojs/document-object-model] Meanwhile, in 2015, the Web Applications group was disbanded and DOM stewardship passed to the Web Platform group.
[src:neutralinojs/document-object-model] Beginning with the publication of DOM Level 4 in 2015, the W3C creates new recommendations based on snapshots of the WHATWG standard.
[src:neutralinojs/document-object-model] To render a document such as a HTML page, most web browsers use an internal model similar to the DOM.
[src:neutralinojs/document-object-model] The nodes of every document are organized in a tree structure, called the *DOM tree*, with the topmost node named as "Document object".
[src:neutralinojs/document-object-model] When an HTML page is rendered in browsers, the browser downloads the HTML into local memory and automatically parses it to display the page on screen.
[src:neutralinojs/document-object-model] However, the DOM does not necessarily need to be represented as a tree, and some browsers have used other internal models.
[src:neutralinojs/document-object-model] When a web page is loaded, the browser creates a Document Object Model of the page, which is an object oriented representation of an HTML document that acts as an interface between JavaScript and the document itself.
[src:neutralinojs/document-object-model] A Document Object Model (DOM) tree is a hierarchical representation of an HTML or XML document.
[src:neutralinojs/document-object-model] It consists of a root node, which is the document itself, and a series of child nodes that represent the elements, attributes, and text content of the document.
[src:neutralinojs/document-object-model] Each node in the tree has a parent node, except for the root node, and can have multiple child nodes.
[src:neutralinojs/document-object-model] Elements in an HTML or XML document are represented as nodes in the DOM tree.
[src:neutralinojs/document-object-model] Each element node has a tag name and attributes, and can contain other element nodes or text nodes as children.
[src:neutralinojs/document-object-model] Text content within an element is represented as a text node in the DOM tree.
[src:neutralinojs/document-object-model] Text nodes do not have attributes or child nodes and are therefore always leaf nodes in the tree.
[src:neutralinojs/document-object-model] For example, the text content "My Website" in the title element and "Welcome" in the h1 element are both represented as text nodes.
[src:neutralinojs/document-object-model] Attributes of an element are represented as properties of the element node in the DOM tree.
[src:neutralinojs/document-object-model] The DOM tree can be manipulated using JavaScript or other programming languages.
[src:neutralinojs/document-object-model] Common tasks include navigating the tree, adding, removing, and modifying nodes, and getting and setting the properties of nodes.
[src:neutralinojs/document-object-model] The DOM API provides a set of methods and properties to perform these operations, such as `getElementById`, `createElement`, `appendChild`, and `innerHTML`.
[src:neutralinojs/document-object-model] Another way to create a DOM structure is using the innerHTML property to insert HTML code as a string, creating the elements and children in the process.
[src:neutralinojs/document-object-model] Another method is to use a JavaScript library or framework such as jQuery, AngularJS, React, Vue.js, Svelte, etc.
[src:neutralinojs/document-object-model] These libraries provide an efficient way to create, manipulate and interact with the DOM.
[src:neutralinojs/document-object-model] It is also possible to create a DOM structure from an XML or JSON data, using JavaScript methods to parse the data and create the nodes accordingly.
[src:neutralinojs/document-object-model] Creating a DOM structure does not necessarily mean that it will be displayed in the web page, it only exists in memory and should be appended to the document body or a specific container to be rendered.
[src:neutralinojs/document-object-model] In summary, creating a DOM structure involves creating individual nodes and organizing them in a hierarchical structure using JavaScript or other programming languages, and it can be done using several methods depending on the use case and the developer's preference.
[src:neutralinojs/document-object-model] Because the DOM supports navigation in any direction (e.g., parent and previous sibling) and allows for arbitrary modifications, implementations typically buffer the document.
[src:neutralinojs/document-object-model] However, a DOM need not originate in a serialized document at all, but can be created in place with the DOM API.
[src:neutralinojs/document-object-model] And even before the idea of the DOM originated, there were implementations of equivalent structure with persistent disk representation and rapid access, for example DynaText's model disclosed in and various database approaches.
[src:neutralinojs/document-object-model] Web browsers rely on layout engines to parse HTML into a DOM.
[src:neutralinojs/document-object-model] Some layout engines, such as Trident/MSHTML, are associated primarily or exclusively with a particular browser, such as Internet Explorer.
[src:neutralinojs/document-object-model] Others, including Blink, WebKit, and Gecko, are shared by a number of browsers, such as Google Chrome, Opera, Safari, and Firefox.
[src:neutralinojs/document-object-model] The different layout engines implement the DOM standards to varying degrees of compliance.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Web browsers have a dedicated JavaScript engine that executes the client code.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] These engines are also utilized in some servers and a variety of apps.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] The most popular runtime system for non-browser usage is Node.js.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] JavaScript is a high-level, often just-in-time–compiled language that conforms to the ECMAScript standard.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] It has dynamic typing, prototype-based object-orientation, and first-class functions.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] It is multi-paradigm, supporting event-driven, functional, and imperative programming styles.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] It has application programming interfaces (APIs) for working with text, dates, regular expressions, standard data structures, and the Document Object Model (DOM).
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] The ECMAScript standard does not include any input/output (I/O), such as networking, storage, or graphics facilities.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] In practice, the web browser or other runtime system provides JavaScript APIs for I/O.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Although Java and JavaScript are similar in name and syntax, the two languages are distinct and differ greatly in design.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] The first popular web browser with a graphical user interface, Mosaic, was released in 1993.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] The lead developers of Mosaic then founded the Netscape corporation, which released a more polished browser, Netscape Navigator, in 1994.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] During these formative years of the Web, web pages could only be static, lacking the capability for dynamic behavior after the page was loaded in the browser.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] There was a desire in the flourishing web development scene to remove this limitation, so in 1995, Netscape decided to add a programming language to Navigator.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] They pursued two routes to achieve this: collaborating with Sun Microsystems to embed the Java language, while also hiring Brendan Eich to embed the Scheme language.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] The goal was a "language for the masses", "to help nonprogrammers create dynamic, interactive Web sites".
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Netscape management soon decided that the best option was for Eich to devise a new language, with syntax similar to Java and less like Scheme or other extant scripting languages.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Although the new language and its interpreter implementation were called LiveScript when first shipped as part of a Navigator beta in September 1995, the name was changed to JavaScript for the official release in December.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] The choice of the *JavaScript* name has caused confusion, implying that it is directly related to Java.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] At the time, the dot-com boom had begun and Java was a popular new language, so Eich considered the JavaScript name a marketing ploy by Netscape.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Microsoft debuted Internet Explorer in 1995, leading to a browser war with Netscape.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] On the JavaScript front, Microsoft created its own interpreter called JScript.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Microsoft first released JScript in 1996, alongside initial support for CSS and extensions to HTML.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Each of these implementations was noticeably different from their counterparts in Netscape Navigator.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] These differences made it difficult for developers to make their websites work well in both browsers, leading to widespread use of "best viewed in Netscape" and "best viewed in Internet Explorer" logos for several years.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] In November 1996, Netscape submitted JavaScript to Ecma International, as the starting point for a standard specification that all browser vendors could conform to.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] This led to the official release of the first ECMAScript language specification in June 1997.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] The standards process continued for a few years, with the release of ECMAScript 2 in June 1998 and ECMAScript 3 in December 1999.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] However, the effort to fully standardize the language was undermined by Microsoft gaining an increasingly dominant position in the browser market.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] By the early 2000s, Internet Explorer's market share reached 95%.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] This meant that JScript became the de facto standard for client-side scripting on the Web.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Microsoft initially participated in the standards process and implemented some proposals in its JScript language, but eventually it stopped collaborating on ECMA work.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] During the period of Internet Explorer dominance in the early 2000s, client-side scripting was stagnant.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] This started to change in 2004, when the successor of Netscape, Mozilla, released the Firefox browser.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Firefox was well received by many, taking significant market share from Internet Explorer.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] In 2005, Mozilla joined ECMA International, and work started on the ECMAScript for XML (E4X) standard.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] This led to Mozilla working jointly with Macromedia (later acquired by Adobe Systems), who were implementing E4X in their ActionScript 3 language, which was based on an ECMAScript 4 draft.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] The goal became standardizing ActionScript 3 as the new ECMAScript 4.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] To this end, Adobe Systems released the Tamarin implementation as an open source project.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] However, Tamarin and ActionScript 3 were too different from established client-side scripting, and without cooperation from Microsoft, ECMAScript 4 never reached fruition.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Meanwhile, very important developments were occurring in open-source communities not affiliated with ECMA work.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] In 2005, Jesse James Garrett released a white paper in which he coined the term Ajax and described a set of technologies, of which JavaScript was the backbone, to create web applications where data can be loaded in the background, avoiding the need for full page reloads.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] This sparked a renaissance period of JavaScript, spearheaded by open-source libraries and the communities that formed around them.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Many new libraries were created, including jQuery, Prototype, Dojo Toolkit, and MooTools.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Google debuted its Chrome browser in 2008, with the V8 JavaScript engine that was faster than its competition.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] The key innovation was just-in-time compilation (JIT), so other browser vendors needed to overhaul their engines for JIT.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] In July 2008, these disparate parties came together for a conference in Oslo.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] This led to the eventual agreement in early 2009 to combine all relevant work and drive the language forward.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] The result was the ECMAScript 5 standard, released in December 2009.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Ambitious work on the language continued for several years, culminating in an extensive collection of additions and refinements being formalized with the publication of ECMAScript 6 in 2015.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] The creation of Node.js in 2009 by Ryan Dahl sparked a significant increase in the usage of JavaScript outside of web browsers.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Node combines the V8 engine, an event loop, and I/O APIs, thereby providing a stand-alone JavaScript runtime system.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] As of 2018, Node had been used by millions of developers, and npm had the most modules of any package manager in the world.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] The ECMAScript draft specification is currently maintained openly on GitHub, and editions are produced via regular annual snapshots.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Potential revisions to the language are vetted through a comprehensive proposal process.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Now, instead of edition numbers, developers check the status of upcoming features individually.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] The current JavaScript ecosystem has many libraries and frameworks, established programming practices, and substantial usage of JavaScript outside of web browsers.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Plus, with the rise of single-page applications and other JavaScript-heavy websites, several transpilers have been created to aid the development process.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] As of 2025, the overwhelming majority of websites (98.9%) use JavaScript for client side webpage behavior.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] "JavaScript" is a trademark of Oracle Corporation in the United States.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] The trademark was originally issued to Sun Microsystems on 6 May 1997, and was transferred to Oracle when they acquired Sun in 2009.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] A letter was circulated in September 2024, spearheaded by Ryan Dahl, calling on Oracle to free the JavaScript trademark.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Brendan Eich, the original creator of JavaScript, was among the over 14,000 signatories who supported the initiative.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] JavaScript is the dominant client-side scripting language of the Web, with 99% of all websites using it for this purpose.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Scripts are embedded in or included from HTML documents and interact with the DOM.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] All major web browsers have a built-in JavaScript engine that executes the code on the user's device.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Over 80% of websites use a third-party JavaScript library or web framework as part of their client-side scripting.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Other notable ones include Angular, Bootstrap, Lodash, Modernizr, React, Underscore, and Vue.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Multiple options can be used in conjunction, such as jQuery and Bootstrap.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] However, the term "Vanilla JS" was coined for websites not using any libraries or frameworks at all, instead relying entirely on standard JavaScript functionality.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] The use of JavaScript has expanded beyond its web browser roots.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] JavaScript engines are now embedded in a variety of other software systems, both for server-side website deployments and non-browser applications.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Initial attempts at promoting server-side JavaScript usage were Netscape Enterprise Server and Microsoft's Internet Information Services, but they were small niches.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Server-side usage eventually started to grow in the late 2000s, with the creation of Node.js and other approaches.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Electron, Cordova, React Native, and other application frameworks have been used to create many applications with behavior implemented in JavaScript.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Other non-browser applications include Adobe Acrobat support for scripting PDF documents and GNOME Shell extensions written in JavaScript.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Oracle used to provide Nashorn, a JavaScript interpreter, as part of their Java Development Kit (JDK) API library along with **jjs** a command line interpreter as of JDK version 8.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] As a replacement Oracle offered GraalJS which can also be used with the OpenJDK which allows one to create and reference Java objects in JavaScript code and add runtime scripting in JavaScript to applications written in Java.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] JavaScript has been used in some embedded systems, usually by leveraging Node.js.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] The first JavaScript engines were interpreters of the source code, but modern engines use just-in-time compilation to improve performance.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] JavaScript engines are typically developed by web browser vendors, and every major browser includes one.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] In a browser, the JavaScript engine runs in concert with the rendering engine via the Document Object Model and Web IDL bindings.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] However, the use of JavaScript engines is not limited to browsers; For example, the V8 engine is a core component of the Node.js runtime system.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] They are also called ECMAScript engines, after the official name of the specification.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] With the advent of WebAssembly, some engines can also execute this code in the same sandbox as regular JavaScript code.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] A JavaScript engine must be embedded within a runtime system (such as a web browser or a standalone system) to enable scripts to interact with the broader environment.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] The runtime system includes the necessary APIs for input/output operations, such as networking, storage, and graphics, and provides the ability to import scripts.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] JavaScript is a single-threaded language.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] The runtime processes messages from a queue one at a time, and it calls a function associated with each new message, creating a call stack frame with the function's arguments and local variables.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] The call stack shrinks and grows based on the function's needs.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] When the call stack is empty upon function completion, JavaScript proceeds to the next message in the queue.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] This is called the event loop, described as "run to completion" because each message is fully processed before the next message is considered.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] However, the language's concurrency model describes the event loop as non-blocking: program I/O is performed using events and callback functions.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] This means, for example, that JavaScript can process a mouse click while waiting for a database query to return information.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] The notable standalone runtimes are Node.js, Deno, and Bun.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] The following features are common to all conforming ECMAScript implementations unless explicitly specified otherwise.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] The number of cited reserved words including keywords is 50–60 and varies depending on the implementation.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] JavaScript supports much of the structured programming syntax from C (e.g., `if` statements, `while` loops, `switch` statements, `do while` loops, etc.).
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] One partial exception is scoping: originally JavaScript only had function scoping with `var`; block scoping was added in ECMAScript 2015 with the keywords `let` and `const`.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Like C, JavaScript makes a distinction between expressions and statements.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] One syntactic difference from C is automatic semicolon insertion, which allow semicolons (which terminate statements) to be omitted.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] JavaScript is weakly typed, which means certain types are implicitly cast depending on the operation used.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Values are cast to numbers by casting to strings and then casting the strings to numbers.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] These processes can be modified by defining `toString` and `valueOf` functions on the prototype for string and number casting respectively.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] JavaScript has received criticism for the way it implements these conversions as the complexity of the rules can be mistaken for inconsistency.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] For example, when adding a number to a string, the number will be cast to a string before performing concatenation, but when subtracting a number from a string, the string is cast to a number before performing subtraction.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Often also mentioned is `{} + []` resulting in `0` (number).
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] This is misleading: the `{}` is interpreted as an empty code block instead of an empty object, and the empty array is cast to a number by the remaining unary `+` operator.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] If the expression is wrapped in parentheses - `({} + [])` – the curly brackets are interpreted as an empty object and the result of the expression is `"[object Object]"` as expected.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] JavaScript is dynamically typed like most other scripting languages.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] A type is associated with a value rather than an expression.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] For example, a variable initially bound to a number may be reassigned to a string.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] JavaScript supports various ways to test the type of objects, including duck typing.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] JavaScript includes an `eval` function that can execute statements provided as strings at run-time.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] In JavaScript, an object is an associative array, augmented with a prototype (see below); each key provides the name for an object property, and there are two syntactical ways to specify such a name: dot notation (`obj.x = 10`) and bracket notation (`obj["x"] = 10`).
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] A property may be added, rebound, or deleted at run-time.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Most properties of an object (and any property that belongs to an object's prototype inheritance chain) can be enumerated using a `for...in` loop.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] JavaScript uses prototypes where many other object-oriented languages use classes for inheritance, but it's still possible to simulate most class-based features with the prototype system.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Additionally, ECMAScript version 6 (released June 2015) introduced the keywords **class**, **extends** and **super**, which serve as syntactic sugar to abstract the underlying prototypal inheritance system with a more conventional interface.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Constructors are declared by specifying a method named **constructor**, and all classes are automatically subclasses of the base class Object, similarly to Java.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Though the underlying object mechanism is still based on prototypes, the newer syntax is similar to other object oriented languages.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Private variables are declared by prefixing the field name with a number sign (#), and polymorphism is not directly supported, although it can be emulated by manually calling different functions depending on the number and type of arguments provided.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Functions double as object constructors, along with their typical role.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Prefixing a function call with *new* will create an instance of a prototype, inheriting properties and methods from the constructor (including properties from the `Object` prototype).
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] ECMAScript 5 offers the `Object.create` method, allowing explicit creation of an instance without automatically inheriting from the `Object` prototype (older environments can assign the prototype to `null`).
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] The constructor's `prototype` property determines the object used for the new object's internal prototype.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] New methods can be added by modifying the prototype of the function used as a constructor.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] JavaScript's built-in classes, such as `Array` and `Object`, also have prototypes that can be modified.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] However, it's generally considered bad practice to modify built-in objects, because third-party code may use or inherit methods and properties from these objects, and may not expect the prototype to be modified.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Unlike in many object-oriented languages, in JavaScript there is no distinction between a function definition and a method definition.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Rather, the distinction occurs during function calling.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] When a function is called as a method of an object, the function's local *this* keyword is bound to that object for that invocation.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] JavaScript functions are first-class; a function is considered to be an object.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] As such, a function may have properties and methods, such as `.call()` and `.bind()`.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] A *nested* function is a function defined within another function.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] It is created each time the outer function is invoked.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] In addition, each nested function forms a lexical closure: the lexical scope of the outer function (including any constant, local variable, or argument value) becomes part of the internal state of each inner function object, even after execution of the outer function concludes.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] JavaScript also supports anonymous functions.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] JavaScript supports implicit and explicit delegation.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] JavaScript natively supports various function-based implementations of Role patterns like Traits and Mixins.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Such a function defines additional behavior by at least one method bound to the `this` keyword within its `function` body.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] A Role then has to be delegated explicitly via `call` or `apply` to objects that need to feature additional behavior that is not shared via the prototype chain.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Whereas explicit function-based delegation does cover composition in JavaScript, implicit delegation already happens every time the prototype chain is walked in order to, e.g., find a method that might be related to but is not directly owned by an object.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Once the method is found it gets called within this object's context.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Thus inheritance in JavaScript is covered by a delegation automatism that is bound to the prototype property of constructor functions.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] An indefinite number of parameters can be passed to a function.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] The function can access them through formal parameters and also through the local `arguments` object.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Variadic functions can also be created by using the `bind` method.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Like in many scripting languages, arrays and objects (associative arrays in other languages) can each be created with a succinct shortcut syntax.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] In fact, these literals form the basis of the JSON data format.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] JavaScript supports regular expressions for text searches and manipulation.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] A built-in Promise object provides functionality for handling promises and associating handlers with an asynchronous action's eventual result.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] JavaScript supplies combinator methods, which allow developers to combine multiple JavaScript promises and do operations based on different scenarios.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] The methods introduced are: Promise.race, Promise.all, Promise.allSettled and Promise.any.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Async/await allows an asynchronous, non-blocking function to be structured in a way similar to an ordinary synchronous function.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Asynchronous, non-blocking code can be written, with minimal overhead, structured similarly to traditional synchronous, blocking code.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Variables in JavaScript can be defined using either the `var`, `let` or `const` keywords.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Variables defined without keywords will be defined at the global scope.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Arrow functions were first introduced in 6th Edition – ECMAScript 2015.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] They shorten the syntax for writing functions in JavaScript.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Arrow functions are anonymous, so a variable is needed to refer to them in order to invoke them after their creation, unless surrounded by parenthesis and executed immediately.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Here is an example of JavaScript syntax.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Note the comments in the examples above, all of which were preceded with two forward slashes.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] More examples can be found at the Wikibooks page on JavaScript syntax examples.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] JavaScript and the DOM provide the potential for malicious authors to deliver scripts to run on a client computer via the Web.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Browser authors minimize this risk using two restrictions.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] First, scripts run in a sandbox in which they can only perform Web-related actions, not general-purpose programming tasks like creating files.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Second, scripts are constrained by the same-origin policy: scripts from one website do not have access to information such as usernames, passwords, or cookies sent to another site.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Most JavaScript-related security bugs are breaches of either the same origin policy or the sandbox.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] There are subsets of general JavaScript—ADsafe, Secure ECMAScript (SES)—that provide greater levels of security, especially on code created by third parties (such as advertisements).
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Closure Toolkit is another project for safe embedding and isolation of third-party JavaScript and HTML.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Content Security Policy is the main intended method of ensuring that only trusted code is executed on a Web page.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] A common JavaScript-related security problem is cross-site scripting (XSS), a violation of the same-origin policy.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] XSS vulnerabilities occur when an attacker can cause a target Website, such as an online banking website, to include a malicious script in the webpage presented to a victim.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] The script in this example can then access the banking application with the privileges of the victim, potentially disclosing secret information or transferring money without the victim's authorization.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] One important solution to XSS vulnerabilities is HTML sanitization.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Some browsers include partial protection against *reflected* XSS attacks, in which the attacker provides a URL including malicious script.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] However, even users of those browsers are vulnerable to other XSS attacks, such as those where the malicious code is stored in a database.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Only correct design of Web applications on the server-side can fully prevent XSS.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] XSS vulnerabilities can also occur because of implementation mistakes by browser authors.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Another cross-site vulnerability is cross-site request forgery (CSRF).
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] In CSRF, code on an attacker's site tricks the victim's browser into taking actions the user did not intend at a target site (like transferring money at a bank).
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] When target sites rely solely on cookies for request authentication, requests originating from code on the attacker's site can carry the same valid login credentials of the initiating user.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] In general, the solution to CSRF is to require an authentication value in a hidden form field, and not only in the cookies, to authenticate any request that might have lasting effects.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Checking the HTTP Referrer header can also help.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] "JavaScript hijacking" is a type of CSRF attack in which a `<script>` tag on an attacker's site exploits a page on the victim's site that returns private information such as JSON or JavaScript.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Developers of client-server applications must recognize that untrusted clients may be under the control of attackers.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] The author of an application should not assume that their JavaScript code will run as intended (or at all) because any secret embedded in the code could be extracted by a determined adversary.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Package management systems such as npm and Bower are popular with JavaScript developers.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Such systems allow a developer to easily manage their program's dependencies upon other developers' program libraries.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Developers trust that the maintainers of the libraries will keep them secure and up to date, but that is not always the case.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] A vulnerability has emerged because of this blind trust.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Relied-upon libraries can have new releases that cause bugs or vulnerabilities to appear in all programs that rely upon the libraries.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Inversely, a library can go unpatched with known vulnerabilities out in the wild.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] In a study done looking over a sample of 133,000 websites, researchers found 37% of the websites included a library with at least one known vulnerability.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] This occurred in March 2016 when Azer Koçulu removed his repository from npm.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] This caused tens of thousands of programs and websites depending upon his libraries to break.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] JavaScript provides an interface to a wide range of browser capabilities, some of which may have flaws such as buffer overflows.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] These flaws can allow attackers to write scripts that would run any code they wish on the user's system.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] This code is not by any means limited to another JavaScript application.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] For example, a buffer overrun exploit can allow an attacker to gain access to the operating system's API with superuser privileges.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] These flaws have affected major browsers including Firefox, Internet Explorer, and Safari.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Plugins, such as video players, Adobe Flash, and the wide range of ActiveX controls enabled by default in Microsoft Internet Explorer, may also have flaws exploitable via JavaScript (such flaws have been exploited in the past).
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] In Windows Vista, Microsoft has attempted to contain the risks of bugs such as buffer overflows by running the Internet Explorer process with limited privileges.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Google Chrome similarly confines its page renderers to their own "sandbox".
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Web browsers are capable of running JavaScript outside the sandbox, with the privileges necessary to, for example, create or delete files.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Such privileges are not intended to be granted to code from the Web.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Incorrectly granting privileges to JavaScript from the Web has played a role in vulnerabilities in both Internet Explorer and Firefox.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] In Windows XP Service Pack 2, Microsoft demoted JScript's privileges in Internet Explorer.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Microsoft Windows allows JavaScript source files on a computer's hard drive to be launched as general-purpose, non-sandboxed programs (see: Windows Script Host).
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] This makes JavaScript (like VBScript) a theoretically viable vector for a Trojan horse, although JavaScript Trojan horses are uncommon in practice.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] In 2015, a JavaScript-based proof-of-concept implementation of a rowhammer attack was described in a paper by security researchers.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] In 2017, a JavaScript-based attack via browser was demonstrated that could bypass ASLR.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] In 2018, the paper that announced the Spectre attacks against Speculative Execution in Intel and other processors included a JavaScript implementation.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Important tools have evolved with the language.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] A common misconception is that JavaScript is directly related to Java.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Both indeed have a C-like syntax (the C language being their most immediate common ancestor language).
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] They are also typically sandboxed, and JavaScript was designed with Java's syntax and standard library in mind.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] In particular, all Java keywords were reserved in original JavaScript, JavaScript's standard library follows Java's naming conventions, and JavaScript's `Math` and `Date` objects are based on classes from Java 1.0.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Both languages first appeared in 1995, but Java was developed by James Gosling of Sun Microsystems and JavaScript by Brendan Eich of Netscape Communications.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] The differences between the two languages are more prominent than their similarities.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Java has static typing, while JavaScript's typing is dynamic.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Java is loaded from compiled bytecode, while JavaScript is loaded as human-readable source code.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Java's objects are class-based, while JavaScript's are prototype-based.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Finally, Java did not support functional programming until Java 8, while JavaScript has done so from the beginning, being influenced by Scheme.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] JSON is a data format derived from JavaScript; hence the name JavaScript Object Notation.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] It is a widely used format supported by many other programming languages.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] Many websites are JavaScript-heavy, so transpilers have been created to convert code written in other languages, which can aid the development process.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] TypeScript and CoffeeScript are two notable languages that transpile to JavaScript.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] WebAssembly is a newer language with a bytecode format designed to complement JavaScript, especially the performance-critical portions of web page scripts.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] All of the major JavaScript engines support WebAssembly, which runs in the same sandbox as regular JavaScript code.
[src:neutralinojs/javascript] asm.js is a subset of JavaScript that served as the forerunner of WebAssembly.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] A **single-page application** (**SPA**) is a web application or website that interacts with the user by dynamically rewriting the current web page with new data from the web server, instead of the default method of loading entire new pages.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] The goal is faster transitions that make the website feel more like a native app.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] In a SPA, a page refresh never occurs; instead, all necessary HTML, JavaScript, and CSS code is either retrieved by the browser with a single page load, or the appropriate resources are dynamically loaded and added to the page as necessary, usually in response to user actions.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] The origins of the term *single-page application* are unclear, though the concept was discussed at least as early as 2003 by technology evangelists from Netscape.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] Earlier forms were called rich web applications.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] JavaScript can be used in a web browser to display the user interface (UI), run application logic, and communicate with a web server.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] Mature free libraries are available that support the building of a SPA, reducing the amount of JavaScript code developers have to write.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] There are various techniques available that enable the browser to retain a single page even when the application requires server communication.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] HTML authors can leverage element IDs to show or hide different sections of the HTML document.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] Then, using CSS, authors can use the `:target` pseudo-class selector to only show the section of the page which the browser navigated to.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] Web browser JavaScript frameworks and libraries, such as Angular, Ember.js, ExtJS, Knockout.js, Meteor.js, React, Vue.js, and Svelte have adopted SPA principles.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] Aside from ExtJS, all of these are free.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] JavaScript-based web application frameworks, such as React and Vue, provide extensive capabilities but come with associated trade-offs.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] These frameworks often extend or enhance features available through native web technologies, such as routing, component-based development, and state management.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] Frameworks can introduce abstraction layers that may contribute to performance overhead, larger bundle sizes, and increased complexity.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] Modern frameworks, such as React 18 and Vue 3, address these challenges with features like concurrent rendering, tree-shaking, and selective hydration.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] While these advancements improve rendering efficiency and resource management, their benefits depend on the specific application and implementation context.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] Lightweight frameworks, such as Svelte and Preact, take different architectural approaches, with Svelte eliminating the virtual DOM entirely in favor of compiling components to efficient JavaScript code, and Preact offering a minimal, compatible alternative to React.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] Framework choice depends on an application’s requirements, including the team’s expertise, performance goals, and development priorities.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] A newer category of web frameworks, including enhance.dev, Astro, and Fresh, leverages native web standards while minimizing abstractions and development tooling.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] These solutions emphasize progressive enhancement, server-side rendering, and optimizing performance.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] Astro renders static HTML by default while hydrating only interactive parts.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] Fresh focuses on server-side rendering with zero runtime overhead.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] Enhance.dev prioritizes progressive enhancement patterns using Web Components.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] While these tools reduce reliance on client-side JavaScript by shifting logic to build-time or server-side execution, they still use JavaScript where necessary for interactivity.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] This approach makes them particularly suitable for performance-critical and content-focused applications.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] The following frameworks utilize WebAssembly or can build single-page applications (SPAs) with WebAssembly as a core technology or support mechanism.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] These frameworks enable high-performance and interactive client-side development, extending the SPA paradigm across languages and ecosystems.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] As of 2006, the most prominent technique used was Ajax.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] Ajax involves using asynchronous requests to a server for XML or JSON data, such as with JavaScript's XMLHttpRequest or more modern `fetch()` (since 2017), or the deprecated ActiveX Object.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] In contrast to the declarative approach of most SPA frameworks, with Ajax the website directly uses JavaScript or a JavaScript library such as jQuery to manipulate the DOM and edit HTML elements.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] Ajax has further been popularized by libraries like jQuery, which provides a simpler syntax and normalizes Ajax behavior across different browsers which historically had varying behavior.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] WebSockets are a bidirectional real-time client-server communication technology that are part of the HTML specification.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] For real-time communication, their use is superior to Ajax in terms of performance and simplicity.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] Server-sent events (SSEs) is a technique whereby servers can initiate data transmission to browser clients.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] Once an initial connection has been established, an event stream remains open until closed by the client.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] SSEs are sent over traditional HTTP and have a variety of features that WebSockets lack by design such as automatic reconnection, event IDs, and the ability to send arbitrary events.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] Although this method is outdated, asynchronous calls to the server may also be achieved using browser plug-in technologies such as Silverlight, Flash, or Java applets.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] Requests to the server typically result in either raw data (e.g., XML or JSON), or new HTML being returned.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] In the case where HTML is returned by the server, JavaScript on the client updates a partial area of the DOM (Document Object Model).
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] When raw data is returned, JavaScript on the client translates it into HTML using XSL or a JSON template before updating the DOM.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] A SPA moves logic from the server to the client, with the role of the web server evolving into a pure data API or web service.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] This architectural shift has, in some circles, been coined "Thin Server Architecture" to highlight that complexity has been moved from the server to the client, with the argument that this ultimately reduces overall complexity of the system.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] The server keeps the necessary state in memory of the client state of the page.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] In this way, when any request hits the server (usually user actions), the server sends the appropriate HTML and/or JavaScript with the concrete changes to bring the client to the new desired state (usually adding/deleting/updating a part of the client DOM).
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] At the same time, the state in server is updated.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] Most of the logic is executed on the server, and HTML is usually also rendered on the server.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] In some ways, the server simulates a web browser, receiving events and performing delta changes in server state which are automatically propagated to client.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] This is a variant of the stateful server approach.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] The client page sends data representing its current state to the server, usually through Ajax requests.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] This approach requires that more data be sent to the server and may require more computational resources per request to partially or fully reconstruct the client page state in the server.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] At the same time, this approach is more easily scalable because there is no per-client page data kept in the server and, therefore, Ajax requests can be dispatched to different server nodes with no need for session data sharing or server affinity.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] Some SPAs may be executed from a local file using the file URI scheme.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] This gives users the ability to download the SPA from a server and run the file from a local storage device, without depending on server connectivity.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] If such a SPA wants to store and update data, it must use browser-based Web Storage.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] These applications benefit from advances available with HTML.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] Because the SPA is an evolution away from the stateless page-redraw model that browsers were originally designed for, some new challenges have emerged.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] Because of the lack of JavaScript execution on crawlers of some popular Web search engines, SEO (search engine optimization) has historically presented a problem for public facing websites wishing to adopt the SPA model.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] Between 2009 and 2015, Google Webmaster Central proposed and then recommended an "AJAX crawling scheme" using an initial exclamation mark in fragment identifiers for stateful AJAX pages (`#!`).
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] Special behavior must be implemented by the SPA site to allow extraction of relevant metadata by the search engine's crawler.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] For search engines that do not support this URL hash scheme, the hashed URLs of the SPA remain invisible.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] These "hash-bang" URIs have been considered problematic by a number of writers including Jeni Tennison at the W3C because they make pages inaccessible to those who do not have JavaScript activated in their browser.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] They also break HTTP referer headers as browsers are not allowed to send the fragment identifier in the Referer header.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] In 2015, Google deprecated their hash-bang AJAX crawling proposal.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] Alternatively, applications may render the first page load on the server and subsequent page updates on the client.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] This is traditionally difficult, because the rendering code might need to be written in a different language or framework on the server and in the client.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] Using logic-less templates, cross-compiling from one language to another, or using the same language on the server and the client may help to increase the amount of code that can be shared.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] In 2018, Google introduced dynamic rendering as another option for sites wishing to offer crawlers a non-JavaScript heavy version of a page for indexing purposes.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] Dynamic rendering switches between a version of a page that is rendered client-side and a pre-rendered version for specific user agents.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] This approach involves your web server detecting crawlers (via the user agent) and routing them to a renderer, from which they are then served a simpler version of HTML content.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] As of 2024, Google no longer recommends dynamic rendering, suggesting "server-side rendering, static rendering, or hydration" instead.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] Because SEO compatibility is not trivial in SPAs, SPAs are commonly not used in a context where search engine indexing is either a requirement, or desirable.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] Use cases include applications that surface private data hidden behind an authentication system.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] In the cases where these applications are consumer products, often a classic "page redraw" model is used for the applications landing page and marketing site, which provides enough meta data for the application to appear as a hit in a search engine query.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] Blogs, support forums, and other traditional page redraw artifacts often sit around the SPA that can seed search engines with relevant terms.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] As of 2021 and Google specifically, SEO compatibility for a plain SPA is straightforward and requires just a few simple conditions to be met.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] One way to increase the amount of code that can be shared between servers and clients is to use a logic-less template language like Mustache or Handlebars.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] Such templates can be rendered from different host languages, such as Ruby on the server and JavaScript in the client.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] However, merely sharing templates typically requires duplication of business logic used to choose the correct templates and populate them with data.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] Rendering from templates may have negative performance effects when only updating a small portion of the page—such as the value of a text input within a large template.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] Replacing an entire template might also disturb a user's selection or cursor position, where updating only the changed value might not.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] To avoid these problems, applications can use UI data bindings or granular DOM manipulation to only update the appropriate parts of the page instead of re-rendering entire templates.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] With a SPA being, by definition, "a single page", the model breaks the browser's design for page history navigation using the "forward" or "back" buttons.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] This presents a usability impediment when a user presses the back button, expecting the previous screen state within the SPA, but instead, the application's single page unloads and the previous page in the browser's history is presented.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] The traditional solution for SPAs has been to change the browser URL's hash fragment identifier in accord with the current screen state.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] This can be achieved with JavaScript, and causes URL history events to be built up within the browser.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] As long as the SPA is capable of resurrecting the same screen state from information contained within the URL hash, the expected back-button behavior is retained.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] To further address this issue, the HTML specification has introduced pushState and replaceState providing programmatic access to the actual URL and browser history.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] Analytics tools such as Google Analytics rely heavily upon entire new pages loading in the browser, initiated by a new page load.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] After the first page load, all subsequent page and content changes are handled internally by the application, which should simply call a function to update the analytics package.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] Failing to call such a function, the browser never triggers a new page load, nothing gets added to the browser history, and the analytics package has no idea who is doing what on the site.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] Similarly to the problems encountered with search engine crawlers, DAST tools may struggle with these JavaScript-rich applications.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] Problems can include the lack of hypertext links, memory usage concerns and resources loaded by the SPA typically being made available by an Application Programming Interface or API.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] Single-page applications are still subject to the same security risks as traditional web pages such as Cross-Site Scripting (XSS), but also a host of other unique vulnerabilities such as data exposure via API and client-side logic and client-side enforcement of server-side security.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] In order to effectively scan a single-page application, a DAST scanner must be able to navigate the client-side application in a reliable and repeatable manner to allow discovery of all areas of the application and interception of all requests that the application sends to remote servers (e.g.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] It is possible to add page load events to a SPA using the HTML History API; this will help integrate analytics.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] The difficulty comes in managing this and ensuring that everything is being tracked accurately – this involves checking for missing reports and double entries.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] Some frameworks provide free analytics integrations addressing most of the major analytics providers.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] Developers can integrate them into the application and make sure that everything is working correctly, but there is no need to do everything from scratch.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] There are some ways of speeding up the initial load of a SPA, such as selective prerendering of the SPA landing/index page, caching and various code splitting techniques including lazy-loading modules when needed.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] But it's not possible to get away from the fact that it needs to download the framework, at least some of the application code; and will hit an API for data if the page is dynamic.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] This is a "pay me now, or pay me later" trade-off scenario.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] The question of performance and wait-times remains a decision that the developer must make.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] A SPA is fully loaded in the initial page load and then page regions are replaced or updated with new page fragments loaded from the server on demand.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] To avoid excessive downloading of unused features, a SPA will often progressively download more features as they become required, either small fragments of the page, or complete screen modules.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] In this way an analogy exists between "states" in a SPA and "pages" in a traditional website.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] Because "state navigation" in the same page is analogous to page navigation, in theory, any page-based web site could be converted to single-page replacing in the same page only the changed parts.
[src:neutralinojs/single-page-application] The SPA approach on the web is similar to the single-document interface (SDI) presentation technique popular in native desktop applications.
[src:neutralinojs/software-framework] A **software framework** is software that provides reusable, generic functionality which developers can extend or customize to create complete solutions.
[src:neutralinojs/software-framework] It offers an abstraction layer over lower-level code and infrastructure, allowing developers to focus on implementing business logic rather than building common functionality from scratch.
[src:neutralinojs/software-framework] Generally, a framework is intended to enhance productivity by allowing developers to focus on satisfying business requirements rather than reimplementing generic functionality.
[src:neutralinojs/software-framework] Frameworks often include support programs, compilers, software development kits, code libraries, toolsets, and APIs that integrate various components within a larger software platform or environment.
[src:neutralinojs/software-framework] Unlike a library, where user code controls the program's control flow, a framework implements inversion of control by dictating the overall structure and calling user code at predefined extension points (e.g., through template methods or hooks).
[src:neutralinojs/software-framework] Frameworks also provide default behaviours that work out-of-the-box, structured mechanisms for extensibility, and a fixed core that accepts extensions (e.g., plugins or subclasses) without direct modification.
[src:neutralinojs/software-framework] A framework differs from an application that can be extended—such as a web browser via an extension or a video game via a mod—in that it is intentionally incomplete scaffolding designed to be completed through its extension points while following specific architectural patterns.
[src:neutralinojs/software-framework] For example, a team using a web framework to develop a banking website can focus on writing banking business logic rather than handling low-level details like web request processing or state management.
[src:neutralinojs/software-framework] According to Pree, software frameworks consist of *frozen spots* and *hot spots*.
[src:neutralinojs/software-framework] *Frozen spots* define the overall architecture of a software system, that is to say its basic components and the relationships between them.
[src:neutralinojs/software-framework] These remain unchanged (frozen) in any instantiation of the application framework.
[src:neutralinojs/software-framework] *Hot spots* represent the parts where the programmers using the framework add their own code to add the functionality specific to their own project.
[src:neutralinojs/software-framework] The necessary functionality can be implemented by using the Template Method Pattern in which the *frozen spots* are known as invariant methods and the *hot spots* are known as variant or hook methods.
[src:neutralinojs/software-framework] The invariant methods in the superclass provide default behaviour while the hook methods in each subclass provide custom behaviour.
[src:neutralinojs/software-framework] When developing a concrete software system with a software framework, developers utilize the hot spots according to the specific needs and requirements of the system.
[src:neutralinojs/software-framework] Software frameworks rely on the Hollywood Principle: "Don't call us, we'll call you." This means that the user-defined classes (for example, new subclasses) receive messages from the predefined framework classes.
[src:neutralinojs/software-framework] Developers usually handle this by implementing superclass abstract methods.
[src:neutralinojs/software-framework] One potential downside of using a framework is that it adds to the size of a program, a phenomenon termed code bloat.
[src:neutralinojs/software-framework] This can be exacerbated by using multiple, sometimes competing, frameworks in the same codebase.
[src:neutralinojs/software-framework] Learning how to use a framework can be substantial.
[src:neutralinojs/software-framework] The intended efficiencies of using the framework may be outweighed by the cost to learn it, especially for a framework that is new to the development staff.
[src:neutralinojs/software-framework] However, once a framework is learned, development team speed may increase for future work.
[src:neutralinojs/software-framework] Some claim that the most effective frameworks evolve from re-factoring an existing solution, such as a generic one-size-fits-all framework developed by third parties for general purposes, rather than from green-field development.
[src:neutralinojs/webview] A **WebView** is a web browser that is embedded within an app.
[src:neutralinojs/webview] Thus, a WebView is a large-scale software component that enables the use of web content within apps.
[src:neutralinojs/webview] In some cases, the entire functionality of the app is implemented this way.
[src:neutralinojs/webview] Other examples are Microsoft's legacy WebView, based on its deprecated EdgeHTML and MSHTML engines, and the WebView component in JavaFX.
